In [[Politics of Austria|Austrian politics]], the '''Ministry of Education''' ([[German language|German]]: ''Bildungsministerium'', historically also ''Unterrichtsminiterium'') is the [[ministry (government)|ministry]] in charge of schools, universities, and arts policy. 

The current head of the Ministry is  [[Heinz Faßmann]]. <ref name="neu">{{cite web | url = https://kurier.at/politik/inland/tuerkis-blau-i-das-sind-die-neuen-minister/302.322.267 | title = Türkis-Blau: Das sind die neuen Minister | date = December 16, 2017 | publisher = Kurier | accessdate = 2018-05-06 }}</ref><ref name="orf">{{cite web | url = http://orf.at/stories/2419283/2419284/ | title = 16-köpfiges ÖVP-FPÖ-Team vereidigt | date = December 16, 2017 | publisher = ORF | accessdate = 2018-05-06 }}</ref>

The ministry was first created in 1848 as the Ministry of Public Schools (''Ministerium für öffentlichen Unterricht''). As of 2018, the agency's official name is '''Ministry of Education, Science and Research''' (''Bundesministerium für Bildung, Wissenschaft und Forschung'' or ''BMBWF''). <ref name="bmgnov">{{cite web | title = Bundesministeriengesetz-Novelle 2017; BGBl. I Nr. 164/2017 | url = https://www.ris.bka.gv.at/eli/bgbl/I/2017/164/20171228 | language = German | date = December 28, 2017 | accessdate = 2018-05-06 }}</ref> <!-- note this is the date of promulgation, not of adoption -->

==Responsibilities==
The Ministry is responsible for all matters regarding public education, including [[Education in Austria#General Education|general education]], [[vocational education|vocational preparatory schools]], [[Adult education]], [[educational research]] and the [[School of education|Pedagogical Universities]].

==History==
The Ministry was first founded in 1848 in the wake of the [[Revolutions of 1848 in the Austrian Empire|Bourgeois revolution]]. Back then, it was named "Ministry for Cultus and Education" and included religious affairs. In the first years of the [[First Austrian Republic]] it was merged into the "Ministry for Interior and Education", until it became its own authority again in 1923. Chancellor [[Bruno Kreisky]] restructured it in 1971, creating the [[Federal Minister of Science, Research and Economy|Ministry of Science and Research]] on one hand and the "Ministry of Education and Arts" on the other. From 2000 to 2007, they were merged again and formed a "Ministry of Education, Science and Culture".

In 2007, the Science Ministry was again established as its own authority. This left the remaining parts as "Ministry for Education, Arts and Culture" ([[German language|German]]: ''Bundesministerium für Unterricht, Kunst und Kultur'', short: ''BMUKK'' or ''Unterrichtsministerium''). It then had additional responsibilities in the fields of Religious foundations and the arts, such as theatre and Film promotion, Museums and related management and funding, such as for the [[Austrian National Library]], and the [[Vienna Philharmonic]]. The [[Bundesdenkmalamt]] was a sub department of the BMUKK as well.

