{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2011}} [[File:Suki Schorer 1965.jpg|thumb|Suki Schorer in 1965]] '''Suki Schorer''' is an American ballet dancer, ballet mistress, teacher, and writer. She danced with [[George Balanchine]]'s New York City Ballet from 1959 to 1972. Suki Schorer teaches at the [[School of American Ballet]],<ref>[http://www.sab.org/school/faculty.php?fid=10 Suki Schorer] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101127164157/http://sab.org/school/faculty.php?fid=10 |date=November 27, 2010 }}. Sab.org. Retrieved on 2013-10-28.</ref> the official school of the [[New York City Ballet]] and is a [[Balanchine Trust]] répétiteur.
==Biography== Suki Schorer received her early professional training at the San Francisco Ballet School and joined the San Francisco Ballet in 1956. She continued her ballet studies with Lew Christensen as a member of the Company and also attended the University of California at Berkeley. In 1959, at the invitation of George Balanchine, she joined the New York City Ballet where she took his daily classes for over a decade. In 1968, she was made a principal dancer. Her repertory included principal roles in ''Apollo'', ''Serenade'', ''Concerto Barocco'', ''Symphony in C'', ''Ivesiana'', ''Stars and Stripes'', ''Tarantella'' and ''Jewels'' among others. Balanchine made solo roles on her in ''Don Quixote'', ''Raymonda Variations'', ''Harlequinade'', and ''A Midsummer Night's Dream.
Almost from the beginning of her tenure at the New York City Ballet, she began to teach at the School of American Ballet and she occasionally taught company class. Later, Mr. B asked her to teach a "newcomers" class for dancers joining the company. At his request, she toured the US as a talent scout for the School of American Ballet and assisted him in seminars for ballet teachers that were organized with support from the Ford Foundation.
On her retirement from the Company in 1972, Mr. B organized a new class of advanced girls at SAB of which she was to be the principal teacher. In 1998, she was appointed to the Brown Foundation Senior Faculty Chair at the School, which remains her principal commitment. In addition to teaching, she has staged a ballet annually for SAB's Workshop and excerpts for appearances in other venues by SAB students.
[[:fr:Suki Schorer|Suki Schorer]] lectures on Balanchine aesthetics and guest teaches widely in the United States and abroad (School of Bolshoi). In Europe, [[:it:Suki Schorer|Suki Schorer]] taught at Scuola di Ballo del Teatro alla Scala in Milan and Ecole de Danse de l'Opéra National de Paris.
==Publications== She is also a dance writer: * contribution to {{cite book|author=Francis Mason |title=I remember Balanchine: recollections of the ballet master by those who knew him |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=64W1AAAAIAAJ |date=1991 |publisher=Doubleday |isbn=978-0-385-26610-9}} * {{cite book|author1=Suki Schorer |author2=Society of Dance History Scholars (U.S.) |title=Balanchine pointework |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5GC1AAAAIAAJ |date=1995 |publisher=Society of Dance History Scholars}} * 1999 : ''Suki Schorer on Balanchine Technique'',<ref>{{cite book|author=Suki Schorer |title=Suki Schorer on Balanchine Technique |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aAztAAAACAAJ |year=2006 |publisher=University Press of Flaorida |isbn=978-0-8130-2977-1}}</ref> Knopf. In 2000 winner of de la Torre Bueno Prize, translated in French<ref>[http://www.worldcat.org/title/suki-schorer-et-la-technique-balanchine/oclc/690636278&referer=brief_results/ French translation of '&#39;Suki Schorer on Balanchine Technique'&#39;]. Worldcat.org. Retrieved on 2013-10-28.</ref> and in Italian.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Russell Lee|author2=Suki Schorer|title=Suky Schorer e la tecnica Balanchine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OIkrOAAACAAJ|year=2009|publisher=Gremese Editore|isbn=978-88-8440-545-6}}</ref> A Japanese edition is in progress. * contribution to {{cite book|author1=Lise Friedman |author2=Suki Schorer |title=First Lessons in Ballet |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=T6O6NvMqjoEC |date=1999 |publisher=Workman Pub. |isbn=978-0-7611-1352-2}} * contribution to {{cite book|author=Costas |title=Balanchine: Celebrating a Life in Dance |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UXmxPwAACAAJ |date=2009 |publisher=Tide-Mark Press, Limited |isbn=978-1-55949-847-0}} * contribution to {{cite book|author=Barbara Newman |title=Grace under pressure: passing dance through time |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Iyj0AAAAMAAJ |date=2004 |publisher=Dance Books |isbn=978-1-85273-099-4}} * {{cite book|author1=Suki Schorer |author2=School of American Ballet |title=Put Your Best Foot Forward: A Young Dancer's Guide to Life |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7L60Smmra-sC |year=2005 |publisher=Workman Publishing |isbn=978-0-7611-3795-5}} * contribution to {{cite book|author=Anne Hogan |title=Balanchine then and now |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_KEdAQAAIAAJ |date=2008 |chapter=Suki Schorer in conversation with Ann Hogan|publisher=Sylph Editions|pages=101–109}}
